    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Da 5 Bloods'",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Da 5 Bloods",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Four Vietnam vets (Delroy Lindo, Clarke Peters, Norm Lewis, Isaiah Whitlock Jr.) go back to retrieve their squad leader's remains and the gold they buried decades earlier; Chadwick Boseman plays that leader in flashback, an idealized, almost Christ-like figure the group still measures itself against. No de-aging for the leads: Lee just cast the actors as themselves, which the hosts land on as purposeful once they clock it. Delroy Lindo's Trump-supporting veteran is the centerpiece: the movie treats his politics as a symptom of untreated trauma rather than a punchline, and pairs the MAGA hat with an OxyContin bottle in the same scene. A landmine set piece involving Jonathan Majors (playing Lindo's son) is singled out as some of the best filmmaking Lee's done in years. Consensus: very good, a genre swing that folds in Coppola, Aldrich, and even Michael Bay, but not quite in the 'Do the Right Thing'/'Malcolm X'/'Inside Man' tier."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
